A Global Marshall Plan for the 21st Century (2026): A Sovereign Contract for Verified Peace and Systemic Stability

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

This doctoral thesis proposes the Global Marshall Plan 2026 (GMP-26), a comprehensive multilateral framework for addressing the convergent crises of armed conflict, economic instability, and institutional fragmentation. Moving beyond metaphor, it defines GMP-26 as a Sovereign Contract: a time-bound, outcomes-based treaty mechanism that makes peace an enforceable, verifiable obligation. The thesis argues that contemporary conflicts are systemic failures of global political economy, requiring not merely aid but a re-engineering of incentive structures.

Inspired by the historical Marshall Plan's integration of economic recovery with political stabilization , GMP-26 modernizes this logic through a Verified Outcomes Framework (VOF) and a Sunset-Linked Charter. The framework is engineered to be directly actionable by international institutions, transforming peace from a moral appeal into a rational, inescapable economic choice. Developed and refined through a Recursive Blueprint Method over four generations of analysis, this work presents a final, stable architecture for a transitional global authority designed to catalyze a phase shift from a world order prone to violent competition to one resilient to it.

